---
// v58 — Writing Room landing. Uses RoomLayout with room="writing"; the
// banner, lower-nav tab strip, and Writing Room tab highlight all render
// from the layout. First occupant is the AI-governance essay at
// /writing/the-only-forever-trust/; further drafts move in as they reach
// working-draft form.
import RoomLayout from '../../layouts/RoomLayout.astro';
---
<RoomLayout
  room="writing"
  title="Writing Room"
  subtitle="First drafts, comments, coauthors."
  width="prose"
  sourceId="writing-index"
>
  <div class="prose prose-slate max-w-none prose-a:text-blue-700 prose-a:underline">
    <p>
      The Writing Room is where the Library's authors compose drafts in
      the open. Essays, working manuals, and primary-source analyses
      live here in working form before they graduate — to <a href="/voices/">Voices</a>
      when they ship as signed editorial pieces, to the Reading Room
      when they reach editorial maturity as published scholarship, or
      to one of the other rooms when their final home becomes clear.
    </p>

    <p>
      This is unusual. Most publishing institutions show only finished
      work; the process by which finished work gets made stays hidden.
      The Library publishes the process too, because the
      cognitive-partnership thesis the project partly advances depends
      on the partnership being visible. Two and a half centuries of
      school-trust history make plain that institutions which conceal
      their working are institutions that drift; institutions whose
      working is in the open are institutions a watchful crew can
      defend.
    </p>

    <p>
      Drafts here are real drafts — not procedural placeholders. They
      argue, they cite, they make their case. They are also incomplete,
      sometimes wrong in detail, and openly seeking comment. If you
      read something here and see a mistake, an omission, or a sharper
      version of the argument, write to the <a href="/reference-desk/">Reference Desk</a>.
      If you have substrate the draft would benefit from — a court
      opinion, a state report, a primary-source document — send it.
      The Writing Room exists because the work the Library is doing is
      bigger than any one author can produce alone.
    </p>

    <h2>In development</h2>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/writing/the-only-forever-trust/">"The Only Forever-Trust We Have Data On"</a></strong>
        (Sullivan, May 2026) — a focused essay taking the eight-anchor
        school-trust-failure-modes argument directly to AI-governance
        designers building the next century's perpetual institutions.
        Working draft, ~2,350 words at skeleton stage. Comments welcome.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      The Library's three book-length manuscripts —
      <a href="/reading/schools-of-the-republic/"><em>Schools of the Republic</em></a>
      (Bird &amp; Sullivan),
      <a href="/reading/sacred-compact/"><em>The Eighth Anchor</em></a>
      (Sullivan), and
      <a href="/reading/wsfc-vol1/"><em>Who Steals from Children, Volume&nbsp;1</em></a>
      (Sullivan) — currently live in the Reading Room. They are
      genuinely works-in-progress and will likely move into the Writing
      Room in a future Library architecture pass; for now their URLs
      remain in <code>/reading/</code>.
    </p>

    <p>
      If you're interested in being a named correspondent for a Writing
      Room draft — an early reader whose comments shape the final
      version — write to the <a href="/reference-desk/">Reference Desk</a>.
      The Library has more substrate than any single author can absorb,
      and the work compounds with co-readers.
    </p>
  </div>
</RoomLayout>
